title: For Sale/Trade:  Very early Browning A5 Light (2 3/4" chamber)
postcontent:
Browning standard model Auto 5 Light 12 gauge shotgun. 
Very early serial number -- serial number 1016.  There are no digits missing it has a four digit serial number. 

26" non-ribbed barrel

2 3/4" inch chamber

Patent date on receiver of 1903. Based on the very early serial number and the patent date I estimate this shotgun was manufactured in late 1903 or early 1904 (there are no record for the guns this early). The first batch of A5s ever manufactured by FN for Browning was 10,000 guns. 

This shotgun has seen a long life of use and careful maintenance and repair and is fully functional.  The receiver was re-blued at some point in the distant past.  It appears like a factory re-bluing and not a home job.   The butt stock and fore grip were also replaced; probably at the same time as the re-bluing.   

Pictures available upon request.

The barrel is a nice 25 1/4" (or 28" from breech to muzzle, and I think the magazine holds 3 or 4. The action is your standard super-strong pump, and works very smoothly. I'm not sure if this was the deluxe model, but the wood is in 100% beautiful in in perfect condition. I believe it's American Walnut, full grain and beautiful, with no dents, dings or damage of any kind. The metal parts are probably in 95% or better, with only a very few blemishes. No rust or corrosion, nor has there ever been. It has your standard safety located behind the trigger, and a brass front bead sight. I believe this is probably a Remington or Mossberg rebranded for Montgomery Ward's Hardware devision (back when MW actually sold stuff that men like!) This was common practice back in the day. There is NO PLASTIC on this shotgun like the new ones... shotguns they sell for cheap at Big 5 and the like have plastic trigger guards, floor plates and furniture/stocks. This gun is all wood and metal, and was probably made in the 1960's or '70's. It must have been a "safe queen" most of it's life, as it is in wonderful condition. All in all this is a nice, well-made pump shotgun for a good price. Buyer pays transfer fee; only $25 in south Mt Vernon. C&R FFL license is OK as well. Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

title: For Sale:  Keltec Sub2000 GEN 2 Glock 19 9mm KEL-TEC SUB 2000
postcontent:
New from Kel-Tec for 2015 is a gun that Kel-Tec fans have been quietly wishing for, but most didn’t not expect. The Sub2000 Gen. 2 is the natural evolution of the folding pistol-caliber-carbine with a few new extras. How do you take a gun that was already solid and make it even better? 

Keeping the form, function, and mechanical action the same, this overhaul focuses on ascetics and ergonomics. Looking at the Gen. 2, the first thing you will notice is that the polymer encasement has been overhauled, trimmed, and textured. Railed surfaces have been added on the top and bottom of the handguard as well as M-lock slots on the sides. 

The front sight has been vastly improved from the first generation. Modeled after an AR-15’s front sight, the Gen. 2 front site is now constructed of metal and is adjustable for windage and elevation. 

The barrel is threaded to 1/2×28 for use with a suppressor. The front sight will need to be removed before a suppressor can be secured the gun. 

The stock of the Gen.2 is also improved, giving the user the option for length-of-pull adjustment, as well as sling mounting surfaces. 

As of now, the Gen.2 will be built in the Glock 17/19/22 pattern, but it will be available with Smith & Wesson M&P, and Springfield Armory XDM pattern magazine wells, too. 

The Sub2000 Gen.2 is a vast improvement over its predecessor and it gives the user a gun that is less of a novelty and more of a real-world option for personal defense. Watch for these innovative guns at your local gun store in the coming months.
